BEGIN_SOLUTION
$BBOLD Part (a) $EBOLD
For the ARMA process given, observe that
$BR
\[
\begin{eqnarray*}
E\left( X\left( t\right) Z\left( t-1\right) \right)  &=&E\left( $alpha X\left( t-1\right) Z\left( t-1\right) +Z\left( t\right)
Z\left( t-1\right) +$beta Z\left( t-1\right) ^{2}\right)  \\
&=&$alpha\times$sigma^{2}+$beta\times 
$sigma^{2} \\
&=& $data[0].
\end{eqnarray*}
\]
$BR

$BBOLD Part (b) $EBOLD
We see that 
\[
\begin{equation*}
E\left( X\left( t\right) Z\left( t\right) \right) =$sigma^{2}.
\end{equation*}
\]
Hence the acvf at lag 0 is$BR
\[ 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\gamma \left( 0\right)  &=&E\left( X\left( t\right) ^{2}\right) -E\left(
X\left( t\right) \right) ^{2} \\
&=&E\left( \left( $alpha X\left( t-1\right) +Z\left( t\right) +
$beta Z\left( t-1\right) \right) \left( $alpha
X\left( t-1\right) +Z\left( t\right) +$beta Z\left( t-1\right)
\right) \right)  \\
&=&$alpha^{2}E\left( X\left( t-1\right) ^{2}\right) +E\left(
Z\left( t\right) ^{2}\right) +2\times $alpha\times $beta E\left( X\left( t-1\right) Z\left( t-1\right) \right)  \\
&&+$beta^{2}E\left( Z\left( t-1\right) ^{2}\right)  \\
&=&$alpha^{2}\gamma \left( 0\right) +$sigma
^{2}+2\times $alpha\times $beta\times $sigma^{2}+$beta^{2}\times$sigma^{2},
\end{eqnarray*}
\]
and so
\[
\begin{equation*}
\left( 1-$alpha^{2}\right) \gamma \left( 0\right) =$sigma^{2}\left( 1+$beta^{2}+2\times $alpha
\times $beta\right) ,
\end{equation*}
\]
from which we see
\[
\begin{eqnarray*}
\gamma \left( 0\right)  &=&\frac{$sigma^{2}\left( 1+$beta^{2}+2$alpha\times $beta\right) }{\left( 1-$alpha^{2}\right) } \\
&=& $data[1].
\end{eqnarray*}
\]
$BR

$BBOLD Part (c) $EBOLD
(c)The acvf at lag 1 is
\[
\begin{eqnarray*}
\gamma \left( 1\right)  &=&\text{Cov}\left( X\left( t\right) ,X\left(
t-1\right) \right)  \\
&=&\text{Cov}\left( $alpha X\left( t-1\right) +Z\left(
t\right) +$beta Z\left( t-1\right) ,\right.  \\
&&\qquad \left. $alpha X\left( t-2\right) +Z\left( t-1\right) + $beta Z\left( t-2\right) \right)  \\
&=&$alpha^{2}\gamma \left( 1\right) +$alpha
\times $sigma^{2}+$alpha\times $beta \times
\left( $alpha+$beta\right) \times $sigma^{2}\\
&&+$beta\times$sigma^{2}, \\
\end{eqnarray*}
\]
where use has been made of the results in (a) and (b). Clearly then
\[
\begin{eqnarray*}
\gamma \left( 1\right)  &=&\frac{$sigma^{2}\left( $alpha+$alpha\times $beta \times t\left( $alpha+$beta\right) +$beta\right) }{\left( 1-$alpha^{2}\right) } \\
&=& $data[2].
\end{eqnarray*}
\]
$BR

$BBOLD Part (d) $EBOLD
For \(k=2,3,\ldots\), 
\[
\begin{eqnarray*}
\gamma \left( k\right)  &=&\text{Cov}\left( X\left( t\right) ,X\left(
t-k\right) \right)  \\
&=&\text{Cov}\left( $alpha X\left( t-1\right) +Z\left(
t\right) +$beta Z\left( t-1\right) ,\right.  \\
&&\qquad \left. $alpha X\left( t-k-1\right) +Z\left(
t-k\right) +$beta Z\left( t-k-1\right) \right)  \\
&=&$alpha\gamma \left( k-1\right),
\end{eqnarray*}
\]
as for an \(\text{AR}(1)\) process. So the acf \(\rho(k)\)$ is determined, dividing \(\gamma(k) \) by \(\gamma(0) \) for each k.
For example,
\[
\begin{eqnarray*}
\rho \left( 2\right)  &=&\frac{\gamma \left( 2\right) }{\gamma \left(
0\right) } \\
&=&\frac{$alpha\gamma \left( 1\right) }{\gamma \left(
0\right) } \\
&=&\frac{$alpha\times$sigma^{2} \times \left( $alpha+$alpha\times $beta \times \left( $alpha+$beta\right) +$beta\right) }{\left( 1- $alpha^{2}\right) \left( $alpha^{2}\gamma
\left( 0\right) +$sigma^{2}+2\times $alpha\times 
$beta\times$sigma^{2}+$beta^{2}\times 
$sigma^{2}\right) } \\
&=& $data[3].
\end{eqnarray*}
\]




